  <body>
    <Header />
    <main class="hist-page">
      <div class="hist-layout">
        <aside class="hist-toc" aria-label="Table of contents">
          <div class="hist-toc-inner">
            <span class="hist-toc-label">Contents</span>
            <ol class="hist-toc-list">
              {toc.map((item) => (
                <li><a href={`#${item.id}`} data-toc-link>{item.label}</a></li>
              ))}
            </ol>
          </div>
        </aside>

        <div class="hist-content">
          <span class="hist-eyebrow">History</span>
          <h1>History of Petrykivka Painting</h1>

          <details class="hist-toc-mobile">
            <summary>Table of contents</summary>
            <ol>
              {toc.map((item) => (
                <li><a href={`#${item.id}`} data-toc-link-mobile>{item.label}</a></li>
              ))}
            </ol>
          </details>

          <article class="hist-article">
            <h2 id="zemlia-stepiv-i-kozakiv">The Land of Steppes and Cossacks</h2>
            <p>
              Petrykivka is an urban-type settlement in the Dnipropetrovsk region, on the right bank
              of the Dnipro. The first reliable documentary mentions of the settlement date back to
              1772; its name is linked to Petro Kalnyshevsky, the last ataman of the Zaporozhian
              Sich, who was involved in founding the settlement on the site of a former Zaporozhian
              winter camp. The village held the status of a state-owned settlement and never knew
              serfdom, and three major fairs were held there every year. This free status of the
              population and its active trade fostered the development of distinctive local crafts,
              among which decorative painting later emerged.
            </p>

            <div class="hist-map">
              <PetrykivkaMap locale="en" />
            </div>

            <h2 id="narodni-vytoky">Folk Origins: Chepurushky and Malyovky</h2>
            <p>
              The Petrykivka region has long been known for its folk craftspeople. At the Petrykivka
              fairs, held three times a year, peasants bought painted ceramics and wooden utensils,
              banduras and spinning wheels, chests and towels decorated with floral patterns, and,
              later, the malyovky themselves.
            </p>
            <p>
              The most capable housewives — those who could do everything well, from whitewashing a
              hut to weaving cloth, embroidering a towel, or painting a wall — were called chepurushky
              in Petrykivka. It was they who passed the craft of painting from generation to
              generation, to daughters and daughters-in-law, and the works of the chepurushky who
              specialized in painting huts and their interiors were valued most highly.
            </p>
            <p>
              From the late 19th century, once bright aniline dyes became widely available, the
              chepurushky began transferring their floral patterns from whitewashed walls onto thin
              sheets of paper — malyovky. These drawings were easy to carry and sell at fairs, and
              over time they gradually displaced mural painting altogether. Wall painting itself
              declined with the onset of collectivization, when peasant life largely lost its former
              joy — and, with it, the desire to decorate the home.
            </p>

            <h2 id="pershi-doslidnyky">The First Researchers</h2>
            <p>
              Only at the turn of the 19th and 20th centuries, as interest in folk art grew, did the
              anonymous paintings of village craftswomen acquire named authorship. Historian and
              ethnographer <a href="/en/masters/dmytro-yavornytskyi">Dmytro Yavornytskyi</a> of
              Yekaterinoslav (now Dnipro) was among the first to reveal the beauty of the Petrykivka
              flower to his contemporaries: by 1905, the museum he had founded in Katerynoslav already
              held numerous household items decorated with Petrykivka painting, and by 1923 the
              museum's collection included roughly a thousand ornamental designs.
            </p>
            <p>
              At Yavornytskyi's request, the artist <a href="/en/masters/yevheniia-evenbakh">Yevheniia
              Evenbakh</a> made watercolour copies of wall paintings during expeditions in 1911 and
              1913, and commissioned small paper drawings from local craftswomen — it is with such
              drawings by <a href="/en/masters/tetyana-pata">Tetyana Pata</a> that the acquaintance
              with Petrykivka ornamental art begins in museum collections. Further research was
              carried out by the art historian
              <a href="/en/masters/yevheniia-berchenko">Yevheniia Berchenko</a> (author of the book
              "Wall Painting of Ukrainian Huts," 1930) and, in the 1960s–70s, by B. Butnyk-Siverskyi
              and <a href="/en/masters/nataliia-hlukhenska">Nataliia Hlukhenska</a>, who wrote the
              first monographic albums on Tetyana Pata and Fedir Panko.
            </p>
            <p>
              A particularly important role in reviving the tradition was played by a local drawing
              teacher, <a href="/en/masters/oleksandr-statyva">Oleksandr Statyva</a> (1898–1966).
              Even before the landmark 1936 exhibition, he had begun collecting samples of the
              chepurushky's work and doing outreach among the village community, insisting on the
              artistic value of this craft. In the early 1930s, Statyva gathered and sent a hundred
              samples of Petrykivka painting to the Kyiv Museum of Ukrainian Art — this selection
              caught the attention of curators in the capital and later became one of the reasons the
              Petrykivka craftswomen were invited to Kyiv (see the section on the 1936 exhibition
              below). Later, in 1966, Statyva wrote the monograph "Master of Decorative Painting
              Nadiya Bilokin" — one of the first scholarly biographical works on Petrykivka
              craftswomen — and he also helped organize the village's school of decorative drawing.
            </p>

            <h2 id="pryroda-yak-dzherelo">Nature as a Source of Inspiration</h2>
            <p>
              The masters of Petrykivka painting have always been united by a deep love for their
              native land. In the floral interlacing of the Petrykivka pattern one can sense the
              fragrance of the herbs, berries, and flowers of the free steppes of the Dnipro region.
            </p>
            <p>
              At the same time, the Petrykivka pattern was never a direct reflection of natural
              motifs — it is a world born of the folk artists' creative imagination: fantastical
              tsybulky ("onions") and kucheryavky ("curlicues"), roses and ferns, firebirds and
              turtle-doves, owls and cuckoos, goldfish swimming out of a mysterious blue ocean. The
              colour scheme settled into a combination of three principal colours — yellow, red, and
              green — typically set against a white background, and the motifs carry their own
              symbolism: the flower as the pinnacle of nature's beauty, the guelder rose and hollyhock
              as symbols of a young woman's beauty, the cuckoo as a symbol of time's eternal motion.
            </p>

            <h2 id="try-chariwnytsi">The Three Petrykivka Charmers</h2>
            <p>
              <a href="/en/masters/tetyana-pata">Tetyana Pata</a>,
              <a href="/en/masters/nadiya-bilokin">Nadiya Bilokin</a>, and
              <a href="/en/masters/yaryna-pylypenko">Iryna Pylypenko</a> — three remarkable
              craftswomen whose names were the first to become widely known.
            </p>
            <p>
              <a href="/en/masters/tetyana-pata">Tetyana Pata</a> was a unique phenomenon even among
              the most outstanding chepurushky — not only an artist with an inimitable style of her
              own, but also the founder of an independent school of decorative painting. Born into a
              poor peasant family of eight children, she mastered the art of painting huts and stoves
              from a young age, creating her paradise gardens of wild and cultivated flowers and
              guelder rose "by eye," yet with great virtuosity.
            </p>
            <p>
              <a href="/en/masters/nadiya-bilokin">Nadiya Bilokin</a> perceived and created her
              pictorial world quite differently — she was a true folk master of detail and
              composition.
            </p>
            <p>
              <a href="/en/masters/yaryna-pylypenko">Iryna Pylypenko</a> was the most traditional of
              the three; her art is most closely tied to the origins of Petrykivka painting, from the
              period when the malyovka still spoke the language of mural painting.
            </p>
            <p>
              Working alongside them were
              <a href="/en/masters/paraska-pavlenko">Paraska Pavlenko</a> (who continued working into
              her hundredth year), <a href="/en/masters/nadiia-tymoshenko">Nadiia Tymoshenko</a>,
              Hanna Pylypenko-Isaieva, <a href="/en/masters/pelaheia-hlushchenko">Pelaheia
              Hlushchenko</a>, and <a href="/en/masters/vasyl-vovk">Vasyl Vovk</a> — each adding their
              own distinctive voice to the shared chorus of Petrykivka masters.
            </p>

            <h2 id="pryrodni-farby">Natural Paints and Tools</h2>
            <p>
              The Petrykivka chepurushky made their paints from whatever the land provided: red from
              cherry juice, green from couch-grass and black nightshade leaves, blue from snowdrop
              flowers, and various shades of yellow from sunflower petals, onion peel, and apple-tree
              bark. The paints were mixed with egg yolk and milk, and fixed with cherry gum or beet
              sugar.
            </p>
            <p>
              From the late 19th century, bright aniline dyes came into use, employed mainly for
              malyovky on paper; watercolour and gouache only became widespread in the postwar years.
              Brushes were made from reed and bulrush stems, and from homemade brushes of cat hair —
              known as "kvachyky" — while bare fingers were also used. Remarkably, Petrykivka masters
              still favour these same tools today over factory-made brushes.
            </p>

            <h2 id="tekhnika-vykonannia">Technique</h2>
            <p>
              Petrykivka painting is done without any preliminary sketch — the master works in a
              single confident stroke of the brush, and correcting a failed mark is practically
              impossible. Two basic strokes form the core vocabulary of Petrykivka brushwork: the
              stroke "away from oneself" (the "comb," or hrebinchyk) and the stroke "toward oneself"
              (the "grain," or zernyatko); combining several of these strokes produces the
              characteristic "little nut" (horishok) element. Plump berries are traditionally applied
              with a fingertip, leaving a slightly convex mark that creates an illusion of volume.
            </p>
            <p>
              A composition is always built asymmetrically: large clusters of flowers or berries are
              sketched first, at the centre of the sheet, and smaller elements are added afterward —
              buds, leaves, delicate "fern" fronds, and the finest strokes and blades of grass known
              as "milloch." Light and shadow are achieved by the simplest technical means: the upper
              part of a petal or leaf is painted in a lighter tone, the lower part in a darker one,
              the colours mixed directly on the brush.
            </p>
            <p>
              Traditional compositional schemes in Petrykivka painting include the "rug" (a dense
              rectangular pattern), the "wreath" or "vensel," the "bouquet," and the "runner" (an
              endless ribbon-like border). Harmonious contrast plays an important role in building a
              composition: a straight line alternates with a curved one, a sharp form with a rounded
              one, and the dominant colour — usually red — is balanced by supporting colours, green
              and yellow, or green and blue.
            </p>

            <h2 id="vyznannia-1936">Recognition: The 1936 Kyiv Exhibition</h2>
            <p>
              The first major exhibition of folk art was held in Kyiv in 1936 — and it was there, with
              the help of <a href="/en/masters/oleksandr-statyva">Oleksandr Statyva</a>, who a year
              earlier had sent a selection of Petrykivka paintings to the Kyiv Museum of Ukrainian
              Art, that a group of Petrykivka craftswomen led by
              <a href="/en/masters/tetyana-pata">Tetyana Pata</a> was invited. In Kyiv, these works
              were recognized as having significant artistic potential, and the exhibition soon
              travelled to Moscow and Leningrad as well.
            </p>
            <p>
              Iryna Pylypenko and <a href="/en/masters/hanna-isaieva">Hanna Isaieva</a> received
              First Class Diplomas; Tetyana Pata and
              <a href="/en/masters/nadiya-bilokin">Nadiya Bilokin</a> returned home with the title of
              Master of Folk Art. The trip proved a turning point: contact with masterpieces of world
              art and the exchange of experience with masters from other regions of Ukraine
              qualitatively changed the Petrykivka malyovka itself — from a simple decoration for a
              village hut, it became an independent work of art. In 1936–1937, Tetyana Pata was
              invited to paint the interiors of the Kyiv Art Institute, and together with Nadiya
              Bilokin and Hanna Pavlenko she decorated the Ukrainian Pavilion at the All-Union
              Agricultural Exhibition in Moscow.
            </p>

            <h2 id="shkola">The Petrykivka School of Decorative Drawing</h2>
            <p>
              Founded through the efforts of
              <a href="/en/masters/oleksandr-statyva">Oleksandr Statyva</a>, the
              <a href="/en/centers/petrykivska-shkola-dekorativnoho-maliuvannia">Petrykivka School of
              Decorative Drawing</a> opened in September 1936 and played a decisive role in shaping
              the craft. Among its most notable students were
              <a href="/en/masters/halyna-prudnikova">Halyna Prudnikova</a>, Vekla Kucherenko,
              <a href="/en/masters/yavdokha-kliupa">Yavdokha Kliupa</a>,
              <a href="/en/masters/ivan-zavhorodnii">Ivan Zavhorodnii</a>,
              <a href="/en/masters/mariia-shyshatska">Mariia Shyshatska</a>,
              <a href="/en/masters/oleksandra-pikush">Oleksandra Pikush</a>,
              <a href="/en/masters/nadiia-shulyk">Nadiia Shulyk</a>,
              <a href="/en/masters/fedir-panko">Fedir Panko</a>,
              <a href="/en/masters/vasyl-sokolenko">Vasyl Sokolenko</a>, and
              <a href="/en/masters/zoia-kudish">Zoia Kudish</a>. The school operated until 1941, when
              its work was cut short by the war.
            </p>
            <p>
              In the 1950s–60s, thanks to numerous exhibitions, Petrykivka art travelled beyond
              Ukraine's borders, and the most talented folk masters were admitted as full members of
              the professional artists' union.
            </p>

            <h2 id="porcelanova-hrupa">Porcelain Painting: The Kyiv Group</h2>
            <p>
              In the postwar years, a group of young students of Tetyana Pata moved from Petrykivka
              to Kyiv — <a href="/en/masters/pelaheia-hlushchenko">Pelaheia Hlushchenko</a>,
              <a href="/en/masters/marfa-tymchenko">Marfa Tymchenko</a>,
              <a href="/en/masters/vira-pavlenko">Vira Pavlenko</a>,
              <a href="/en/masters/hanna-pavlenko-chernychenko">Hanna Pavlenko-Chernychenko</a>, and
              <a href="/en/masters/vira-klymenko-zhukova">Vira Klymenko-Zhukova</a>. Their work
              became closely tied to the Kyiv Experimental Ceramic and Art Factory: with the arrival
              of these Petrykivka artists, a new stage began in the history of Ukrainian porcelain, as
              the achievements of folk ornamental art were systematically transferred onto porcelain
              for the first time.
            </p>
            <p>
              <a href="/en/masters/vira-pavlenko">Vira Pavlenko</a> (1912–1991) worked in a more
              graphic, miniature style, introducing figures of Ukrainian girls in national dress into
              her compositions. <a href="/en/masters/hanna-pavlenko-chernychenko">Hanna
              Pavlenko-Chernychenko</a> (1919–2008), a laureate of the Kateryna Bilokur Prize, combined
              porcelain painting with easel drawing, composing refined two- and three-colour "vazon"
              bouquets. <a href="/en/masters/pelaheia-hlushchenko">Pelaheia Hlushchenko</a>
              (1908–1983) taught at the Kyiv School of Applied Arts from 1937, and her work is marked
              by a more graphic, dense, and refined line — a result of her parallel work in printing
              and book design. <a href="/en/masters/vira-klymenko-zhukova">Vira Klymenko-Zhukova</a>
              (1921–1965) boldly introduced motifs unusual for the tradition in the early 1960s —
              tulips, plums, pears, peppers — along with a new colour palette built on pink, blue, and
              violet.
            </p>
            <p>
              A distinct body of work developed within this milieu belonging to
              <a href="/en/masters/marfa-tymchenko">Marfa Tymchenko</a> (1922–2009), People's Artist
              of Ukraine and laureate of the Taras Shevchenko National Prize of Ukraine. For more than
              thirty years she painted porcelain dinner sets, platters, and vases at the Kyiv
              Experimental Ceramic and Art Factory, and from the early 1970s she turned increasingly
              to decorative-pictorial landscape and folk-picture themes, combining the ornamental
              tradition with narrative painting.
            </p>

            <h2 id="fabryka-druzhba">The Druzhba Factory: Between Souvenir and Art</h2>
            <p>
              In the postwar years, an industrial line of development emerged in Petrykivka itself.
              In 1958, <a href="/en/masters/fedir-panko">Fedir Panko</a> brought together
              self-employed craftspeople into a lacquer-painting workshop at the "Vilna Selianka"
              embroiderers' artel; by the mid-1960s, that workshop had grown into the
              <a href="/en/centers/fabryka-petrykivskyi-rozpys">"Druzhba" factory of art products</a>.
            </p>
            <p>
              The factory's main line of production was under-lacquer painting on pressed sawdust,
              papier-mâché, and plastic — mostly small boxes, decorative plates, and other souvenirs
              coated in black lacquer. It was during this period, under Fedir Panko as the factory's
              chief artist, that a widespread but historically inaccurate notion took hold: that
              Petrykivka painting means a pattern on a black background. Traditionally, a black
              background was never characteristic of Petrykivka painting; this technique was a product
              of factory-souvenir production logic. Painting gradually lost its connection to peasant
              life and became mass-produced merchandise.
            </p>
            <p>
              This was not a personal artistic failure on Panko's part — it was simply what the times
              demanded: factory production had to compete with cheaper industrial souvenirs, and
              without standardization and adaptation to a new material, the Petrykivka craft might
              simply not have survived economically.
            </p>
            <p>
              In the early 1970s, <a href="/en/masters/vasyl-sokolenko">Vasyl Sokolenko</a> changed
              the situation at the factory: he took over the lacquer-painting workshop at Druzhba and
              returned production to the traditional material — wood — leaving the natural colour of
              the wood as the background instead of black lacquer. At the same time, Fedir Panko
              founded his own <a href="/en/centers/eksperymentalnyy-tsekh">experimental creative
              workshop</a> in 1970 at the Dnipropetrovsk Art Production Combine, where he focused no
              longer on mass-produced souvenirs but on high-quality, authored pieces and his own
              artistic pursuits — including a series of panels based on Ukrainian folk songs.
            </p>

            <h2 id="sokolenko">Vasyl Sokolenko</h2>
            <p>
              <a href="/en/masters/vasyl-sokolenko">Vasyl Sokolenko</a> (1922–2018) graduated from the
              Petrykivka School of Decorative Drawing in 1941, having studied directly under Tetyana
              Pata. In the postwar years he worked as a methodologist at the regional house of folk
              art and organized an art studio in the village of Ivanivka, and from 1962 he taught at
              the Petrykivka branch of the Dnipropetrovsk children's art school.
            </p>
            <p>
              For nearly twenty years — from 1971 to 1992 — Sokolenko served as chief artist at the
              <a href="/en/centers/fabryka-petrykivskyi-rozpys">Druzhba factory</a>, and it was he who
              moved production away from black lacquer toward painting on light-coloured wood. He was
              the first to revive wood-based decorative work on an industrial scale — vases, plates,
              salad bowls, ladles, spoons — acting as the author of both the painting and the form
              itself, personally teaching wood-turners how to make the pieces he needed.
            </p>
            <p>
              Sokolenko is also known as a master of the so-called "Petrykivka poster" — graphic works
              that combined decorative ornament with a clear poster-like composition and, often, a
              narrative or symbolic content (a characteristic example is his 1959 work "A Cuckoo
              Among Flowers"). It was on his initiative that a museum of the history of decorative
              painting opened at the Druzhba factory, which the master himself jokingly called "our
              own Louvre."
            </p>
            <p>
              After retiring, Sokolenko built a private house-museum on his own estate —
              <a href="/en/centers/muzei-sadyba-sokolenka">the "Sokolenko Folk Museum"</a> — which
              holds around 600 exhibits, including works by his wife, the craftswoman Hanna Sokolenko,
              with whom he raised five children. The estate remains one of the stops on Petrykivka's
              tourist map today.
            </p>

            <h2 id="nove-pokolinnia">A New Generation: 1970s–1990s</h2>
            <p>
              The 1970s marked a period of generational change: a wave of talented young artists
              appeared at the Druzhba factory and in the experimental workshop —
              <a href="/en/masters/nina-turchyn">Nina Turchyn</a>,
              <a href="/en/masters/vira-tezyk">Vira Tezyk</a>,
              <a href="/en/masters/tamara-kudish">Tamara Kudish</a>,
              <a href="/en/masters/anatolii-chernuskyi">Anatolii and Nina Chernuskyi</a>, Nina
              Hordieieva, Nataliia Kaliuha, Liubov Shtanii, Mariia Kravets,
              <a href="/en/masters/uliana-skliar">Uliana Skliar</a>, Vitalii Panko, and Liubov Bai.
            </p>
            <p>
              Among the leaders of this generation were
              <a href="/en/masters/volodymyr-hlushchenko">Volodymyr Hlushchenko</a>,
              <a href="/en/masters/andriy-pikush">Andrii</a> and
              <a href="/en/masters/mariya-pikush">Mariia Pikush</a>, and
              <a href="/en/masters/hanna-samarska">Hanna Samarska</a>.
              <a href="/en/masters/andriy-pikush">Andrii Pikush</a> absorbed the energy of his
              teachers Panko and Sokolenko, as well as the experience of the Petrykivka elders,
              especially Tetyana Pata; he later opened up the long-forgotten field of ceramics for
              Petrykivka painting, along with the techniques of batik, stained glass, and blown glass.
              <a href="/en/masters/hanna-samarska">Hanna Samarska</a>, who was not born in Petrykivka
              but in Bohdanivka in the Kyiv region, studied under Kateryna Bilokur from 1952 and
              brought her own, highly detailed authorial style to Petrykivka painting.
            </p>
            <p>
              The 1980s brought full creative freedom — Natalia Rybak,
              <a href="/en/masters/valentyna-panko">Valentyna Panko</a>, Nadiia Vasylkivska,
              Valentyna Karpets, Olena Zinchuk, Tetiana Lapshyn, Iryna Nazarenko, and Valentyna
              Milenko all came vividly into their own, alongside the Statyva sisters — Valentyna,
              <a href="/en/masters/lidiia-bulavin">Lidiia</a>, Mariia, and
              <a href="/en/masters/nataliia-statyva-zharko">Nataliia</a>.
            </p>

            <h2 id="dynastii">Petrykivka Dynasties</h2>
            <p>
              The 1980s and 90s gave rise to genuine creative dynasties, in which every generation of
              a family took up the craft — the Shyshatski, Panko, Sokolenko, Pikush, Chernuskyi,
              Tymoshenko, Statyva, Skliar, and Rybak families among them. Thanks to them, the
              tradition continues to pass from parents to children and grandchildren, generation after
              generation.
            </p>

            <h2 id="suchasnyi-stan">Petrykivka Painting Today</h2>
            <p>
              By the end of the 20th century, Petrykivka painting had fully lost its connection to
              peasant life and become, simultaneously, an independent form of authored art and a
              souvenir industry. In 1994, on the initiative of
              <a href="/en/masters/andriy-pikush">Andrii Pikush</a>, a production and creative
              association called "Petrykivka" was formed on the basis of the experimental workshops;
              in 1998 it merged with the experimental workshop to become today's
              <a href="/en/centers/tsentr-narodnoho-mystectva">Petrykivka Centre of Folk Art</a>,
              which today brings together several dozen of the village's leading masters. It was an
              exhibition prepared by the Centre's masters that formed the basis of Petrykivka
              painting's submission to UNESCO.
            </p>
            <p>
              At the same time, the industrial line of development went into decline: the
              <a href="/en/centers/fabryka-petrykivskyi-rozpys">Druzhba factory</a> halted operations
              in 2004 and was formally liquidated in 2006 — a fate typical of many Soviet-era folk art
              enterprises after Ukraine gained independence. Individual authored practice and the
              teaching of the tradition, however, did not stop: since 2012, the Dnipro Theatre and Art
              College has offered a dedicated specialization in Petrykivka painting, taught by
              Honoured Master of Folk Art of Ukraine <a href="/en/masters/tetiana-harkava">Tetiana
              Harkava</a> — a student of Fedir Panko who considers herself part of the fourth
              generation of masters, and her own students part of the fifth.
            </p>
            <p>
              <a href="/en/masters/halyna-nazarenko">Halyna Nazarenko</a> (b. 1968) has also made a
              significant contribution to Petrykivka painting's contemporary life. A member of the
              National Union of Folk Art Masters of Ukraine, she has painted church interiors in Kyiv
              and taken part in dozens of exhibitions in France, the United States, Georgia, China,
              and elsewhere; following exhibitions in France, she was admitted to the Association of
              Contemporary Art of Morestel. Nazarenko actively advocates for Petrykivka painting to be
              recognized as "high art," not merely a souvenir craft, and emphasizes the need for a
              contemporary approach to promoting it — including through new cultural spaces in
              Petrykivka itself.
            </p>
            <p>
              On December 5, 2013, at the eighth session of the UNESCO Intergovernmental Committee for
              the Safeguarding of the Intangible Cultural Heritage, held in Baku, Petrykivka painting
              was inscribed on the Representative List of the Intangible Cultural Heritage of
              Humanity — making Petrykivka the first entry from Ukraine to receive this status. That
              same year, an exhibition titled "Petrykivka Painting — The Colour of Tradition" was held
              at UNESCO headquarters in Paris. The craft became a symbol of the country well beyond
              art circles: Ukraine's postal service issues stamps featuring reproductions of
              Petrykivka patterns, and in 2016 the National Bank of Ukraine issued commemorative coins
              titled "Petrykivka Painting." Since 2007, an annual folk-art festival called
              <a href="/en/centers/petrykivskyi-dyvocvit">"Petrykivskyi Dyvotsvit"</a> ("Petrykivka's
              Magic Bloom") has been held in Petrykivka (and, in 2013–2014, in Dnipro), and it has
              since grown into an international event.
            </p>
            <p>
              Today's masters carry on the tradition with the same tools their predecessors used a
              century ago — handmade cat-hair brushes, reed stems, their own fingers — while also
              working with acrylic paints and painting on glass, metal, and textiles, exploring new
              surfaces and formats. Significant collections of Petrykivka painting are held today by
              the <a href="/en/centers/dniprovskyi-khudozhnii-muzei">Dnipro Art Museum</a>, the
              <a href="/en/centers/muzei-yavornytskogo">Dmytro Yavornytskyi National Historical Museum
              of Dnipro</a>, and the <a href="/en/centers/petrykivskyi-muzei-etnohrafii">Petrykivka
              Museum of Ethnography, Everyday Life, and Applied Art</a>.
            </p>

            <h2 id="vysnovok">Conclusion</h2>
            <p>
              One can encounter the masters of Petrykivka painting not only in Petrykivka itself —
              rich collections of their work are held in museums across Dnipro, Kyiv, and other
              Ukrainian cities. Petrykivka decorative painting is one of the unique phenomena of
              Ukrainian artistic culture: an art free of foreign admixture or influence, embodying the
              spiritual wealth and creative generosity of the Ukrainian people, and one that continues
              to develop today, more than a century after the first recorded malyovky.
            </p>
          </article>

